Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults".

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
5e4918d9-4f09-4800-a62f-f5e9ee1c0062.36a38dae-24f9-4d4f-a658-a24b5b40d40e.prompt=Protocol\: 5e4918d9-4f09-4800-a62f-f5e9ee1c0062.3e744478-cb4c-414c-9048-de7e9673d8c5.prompt=Notification option\: 5e4918d9-4f09-4800-a62f-f5e9ee1c0062.42ba1cd5-fb87-4a08-944c-254ded542bbb.description=
Runs a TraceRoute command either locally or remotely depending on the specified protocol. Credentials and other inputs (remoteOS, hostname, username, password, keyFile etc) are required if the command must be run from a remote host. The Telnet protocol also requires inputs for usernamePrompt and passwordPrompt. 

Inputs\:
    hostname - Hostname or IP address of the host computer where the TraceRoute command will be executed.
    username - A username to authenticate to the host computer. 
    password - The password for the user account.
    targetHost - Hostname or IP address of the target host computer.
    protocol - The protocol used to run the command.
Valid values\: local, ssh, Telnet
    maxHops - The maximum number of hops allowed to trace over while searching for the target host.
    timeout - The timeout in milliseconds.
    remoteOS - The operating system of the host computer (WINDOWS, LINUX, SOLARIS only are supported), if TraceRoute is running on a remote host.
    usernamePrompt - The username prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used.
    passwordPrompt - The password prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used.
    keyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.

Responses\:
    success - The command executed successfully.
    failure - The command could not be executed or had a problem during execution.

Returns\:
    address - The IP address of the target host.
    hops - A list of hosts that the packets traversed en route to the destination.
    times - The round trip times from the host to the hop (latency). 3 packets are sent to each hop along the route.
    returnResult - Raw output of the command.
    returnCode - Return code from the executed command.
    error - The STDERR of the command.

No route exists. Last host reached was ${lastAddress}. IPs of ${host} are ${addresses}. 5e4918d9-4f09-4800-a62f-f5e9ee1c0062.d18f634d-65aa-4a8e-bca7-d36f8fbe3222.prompt=Notification option\: 5e4918d9-4f09-4800-a62f-f5e9ee1c0062.description=
This flow uses a trace route to attempt to localize a network failure.

Note\: if a route cannot be found, it will take a long time to enumerate each hop. If this happens 
at the beginning of the trace route, the trace route may time out with a 500 server error. In this
 case, decrease the maxhops count.

Also, if the traceroute is done from a Windows host, response times of "< 1 ms" can be reported. 
These are rounded up to 1 by this flow, for calculation purposes, and the average time calculations 
might be affected. If you need more accurate measurements of time, use a Linux or Solaris host to 
do the traceroute from. 

Inputs\:
target - The host to traceroute to.
host - The host to traceroute from.
username - Username for host. Required if protocol is not 'local'
password - Password for the user.
protocol - The protocol used to run the command (ssh, Telnet, WMI or local are supported).
notifyMethod - How the user should be informed of the diagnostic's output.
remoteOS - If running a command on a remote host, what is the OS of the remote host (supported\: WINDOWS, LINUX, SOLARIS).
usernamePrompt - The username prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used.
passwordPrompt - The password prompt seen while using Telnet protocol. This input is required when Telnet protocol is used.
hops - The maximum number of hops to traceroute over. Defaults to 30 hops.
hopTimeThreshold - The maximum acceptable time between hops, in milliseconds. Defaults to 30 milliseconds.
timeout - The timeout in milliseconds.
keyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host..
diagnostic so far - The diagnostic so far, used for chaining diagnostics.

Responses\:
success - The operation was successful.
failure - The operation failed.

Returns\:
A human readable diagnostic (updated diagnostic so far).

flow.name: TraceRoute Diagnostic

staticBinding.value: TraceRoute Diagnostic could not compute ping average time/ping time difference.

Unable to trace a route to ${target} from ${host}. The recommended resolution is: 1. Ensure ${target} and ${host} have DNS entries. 2. Ensure the Operations Orchestration Server can contact other systems on the network. 3. Verify the username and password.
Traceroute long hop check for node ${address}

A route could not be found to ${target} from ${host}. The last server on the traced route was ${lastAddress}. The recommended procedure for resolving this issue is: 1. Ensure ${lastAddress} has a route to ${target}. 2. Or change the routing table on a hop before ${lastAddress} to use a different route to ${host}.
